\pagebreakNum

#### Improvised Weapons
Sometimes characters don't have their weapons and have to attack with whatever is at hand. An improvised weapon includes any object you can wield in one or two hands, such as broken glass, a table leg, a frying pan, a wagon wheel, or a murloc.

Often, an improvised weapon is similar to an actual weapon and can be treated as such. For example, a table leg is akin to a club. At the DM's option, a character proficient with a weapon can use a similar object as if it were that weapon and use his or her proficiency bonus.

An object that bears no resemblance to a weapon deals 1d4 damage (the DM assigns a damage type appropriate to the object). If a character uses a ranged weapon to make a melee attack, or throws a melee weapon that does not have the thrown property, it also deals 1d4 damage. An improvised thrown weapon has a normal range of 20 feet and a long range of 60 feet.

#### Adamantine Weapons
The are several metals and materials on Azeroth are ultrahard, or "adamantine," and can be used in the crafting of weapons and armor. Certain monsters that have immunity or resistance to nonmagical weapons can be damaged normally by an adamantine weapon, and adamantine weapons automatically deal critical hits when they hit an object. 

The adamantine version of a melee weapon or of ten pieces of ammunition costs 500 sp more than the normal version, whether the weapon or ammunition is made of the metal or coated with it.

#### Silvered Weapons
Some monsters that have immunity or resistance to nonmagical weapons are susceptible to silver weapons, so cautious adventurers invest extra coin to plate their weapons with silver. You can silver a single weapon or ten pieces of ammunition for 100 sp. This cost represents not only the price of the silver, but the time and expertise needed to add silver to the weapon without making it less effective.

**NOTE:** Check how many creatures are affected by silver.

#### Simple Weapons
These weapons are simple in form or are similar in style and function to everyday items, making them easy to use effectively even with minimal training.

***Bayonet.*** The bayonet can 

If the bayonet is used when not attached to a two-handed firearm, it is considered an improvised weapon.

This blade can be attached or removed from the end of a crossbow or firearm as an action, allowing it to be used it to be used as a melee weapon instead of an improvised one. In order to use the bayonet's versatile property, the attached weapon must have the two-handed property. While the most common form of bayonet is a slim blade for piercing, other forms of bayonet exist such as those that appear as axe blades or hammer heads, dealing slashing or bludgeoning damage as appropriate.

***Brass Knuckles.***

***Cestus.***

***Clawed Glove.***

***Club.*** Any simple heavy length can be used as a makeshift club, but a proper club is straight and has a grip sized to fit in the hand.

***Crossbow, Light.*** A light crossbow is drawn by lever action, making it easier for those of low strength to use.

***Dagger.*** A common backup weapon, a dagger is a longer knife designed for combat.

***Dart.*** A dart is essentially an arrow or bolt designed for throwing. It could also be small bits of sharpened metal called shuriken.

***Greatclub.*** A greatclub is a much larger version of a normal club.

***Handaxe.*** Sometimes known as a hatchet or tomahawk, a handaxe is used for splitting firewood or enemy skulls.

***Javelin.*** A light, flexible spear designed for throwing, the javelin can be hurled greater distances than most other weapons.

***Light Hammer.*** Hammers like these are used as often by blacksmiths or carpenters as by warriors.

***Mace.*** This weapon is a heavy weight at the end of a handle made of thick wood or solid metal.

***Quarterstaff.*** A quarterstaff is a simple length of wood often almost as tall as the one carrying it. It is a favorite weapon of many, from peasants, merchants, and travelers to druids, mages, and priests.

